#1 Resected metastatic colon cancer to the liver (T3, N2 (17 of 40) M1 liver)
Mr. Hager is a pleasant 67-year-old male with metastatic colon cancer who underwent partial resection of his metastatic disease in his liver.  He also underwent portal vein embolization with an ultimate plan to return for further evaluation and surgical resection of the right lobe of the liver.
Basic cancer education has been provided to the patient at the request of Dr. Freeman's and Dr. Hernandez's Service.  I have had the opportunity to review the operative report, surgical pathology, laboratory values, and notes in Documents Browser.  I have reviewed these findings with the patient and answered questions.  I have discussed this case in detail with Dr. Fowler, my collaborating physician, who has guided my plan.
We have discussed the characteristics of the cancer, including the type of malignancy, size, grade, lymph node status, and stage of the cancer.
I have explained in-depth with Mr. Hager, his wife, and his daughter the overall tentative plan to have him return in four weeks for evaluation and plan of care making.  He will undergo a CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis and chest, comprehensive laboratory panel including a CEA, postoperative evaluation with Dr. Freeman as well as a formal consultation with us in Medical Oncology.  He understands this and will plan on getting his chemotherapy closer to home either in West Harwich or at SMC in 27516 where he has an additional home.  I have given him my card, he knows to call if there are problems or concerns regarding his potential overall plan but also understands that the ultimate plan has not been yet finalized pending his appointment in four weeks.  He does plan on making contact with his local medical oncologist prior to his arrival at East Texas Memorial Hospital in a month to help ensure continuity of care.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

