Metastatic colon cancer to liver, status-post colon and liver resection (T3, N2 (17 of 40) M1 liver)

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

I have been asked by Dr. Freeman and Dr. Hernandez to visit with Mr. Hager for postoperative education purposes.  Briefly, Mr. Hager is a very pleasant 67-year-old male from Salem, Indiana.  He has been seen here in the past by Dr. Milligan of Cardiology for a history of aortic insufficiency, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia.
1.  September 2010.  Presented with a six-week history of progressive abdominal bloating and cramping.  CT imaging done locally showed a large colon mass and multiple bilobular liver lesions.  Colonoscopy performed showing a partially obstructing mass at the ileocolonic junction.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.  Patient also complained of progressive anorexia and weight-loss.
2.  October 11, 2010.  Taken by Dr. Hernandez and Dr. Freeman for a joint resection.  Operative report not available at time of dictation but did speak with Dr. Hernandez's Service.  Surgical pathology from the liver portions segments III & IV wedge resections note metastatic moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma consistent with a colon primary forming a 3.8- x 3.6- x 3.3-cm mass.  The surgical resection margins is negative for tumor (minimum tumor-free margins 0.1 cm).  One of two pericholedochal lymph nodes positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma consistent with a colon primary with a size of 1.8 x 1.3 x 1.2-cm.  Right hemicolectomy also showing invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma forming a 6.7- x 2.8- x 2.0-cm mass circumferential in the ileal cecal valve region.  Invading through the muscularis propria into the pericolonic fat involving 17 of 40 regional lymph nodes with negative surgical margins.  No other disease noted but the right-side of the liver metastatic deposits left in place and patient underwent a portal vein embolization with intent to return after hypertrophy of the right lobe of the liver for further surgical resection of metastatic disease.
Mr. Hager is continuing to recover from surgery and is currently up sitting in bed during our consultation today.

[end section id="20103"]

